After 8 amazing years, I’m stepping down as Deputy Director and Chief Curator @icaboston. I did the math - in those 8 years I curated 17 exhibitions, published 8 books, made close to 200 acquisitions for the permanent collection, helped to open 1 new space, commissioned 3 major immersive artworks/installations, co-commissioned & curated 1 US pavilion for @venice.art.biennale, and collaborated with scores of amazing colleagues. A huge THANK YOU to all the artists I’ve worked with for the opportunity to collaborate and the incredible gift of your work. How lucky am I to get to work with so many inspirational, visionary artists? You are why I do what I do!  Hearty congratulations to my brilliant colleague @rutherickson, who will take the mantle of Chief Curator at the ICA…………………………… And stay tuned for news of my next chapter!

After two decades of living as an immigrant in the US, I became a naturalized American citizen today. With 350 others from 52 countries, I was sworn in at Boston’s Faneuil Hall. On this occasion, I think about Robert Frank’s classic series The Americans. Exploring art in North Vancouver - Rebecca Belmore’s installation on the facade of @polygongallery titled “Hacer Memoria.” The title of the work is taken from the Pope’s penitential speech in which he recognized the importance of remembering the devastating impacts of the residential school system. Belmore co-opts his phrase “hacer memoria,” or “try to remember,” by highlighting the challenges of not forgetting. In colours that carry significance – blue for the uniforms that students wore and orange to mark the resilience of survivors – the provocative artwork offers an opportunity to acknowledge Indigenous people. Invoking the word “hereafter,” the artist places emphasis on the troubled present and unknown futures. (From Polygon website)

Visited #LizMagor project “LightShed” in Vancouver’s Coal Harbour. Based on the old boat sheds that used to line the shoreline, the artist cast a ½ scale model in aluminum. And as is the case with public art, the surrounds interact in surprising ways with the art - in this case the angle of the hot dog seller’s umbrella amplifies the leaning angle of Magor’s Shed.

#alanisobomsawin exhibition being deinstalled today @vanartgallery after a great run at the Gallery. “Bush Lady” is the only recording made by Alanis Obomsawin, a member of the Abenaki First Nations and best known as one of Canada’s most accomplished and decorated documentary filmmakers. Obomsawin began her career as a singer-songwriter in the 1960s, part of a broad movement of Indigenous artists rallying in new assertions of cultural consciousness, political rights, and reckonings with oppressive colonial history.

I am so excited to present Teresita Fernández’s new installation at Platform at The Armory Show, opening Sept 7 in New York. Part of a stellar group of artists, come on by!!

REPOST @lehmannmaupin Fernández will unveil a new charcoal installation, ‘Island Universe 2’, at @TheArmoryShow next month in the fair’s Platform section. Titled ‘Rewriting Histories’, this special presentation is curated by Eva Respini (@Curator_On_The_Run) and will be on view at the Javits Center in New York, September 7–10.

‘Rewriting Histories’ brings together large-scale works and site-specific installations by artists who challenge accepted beliefs surrounding history, art, and culture. The presentation will feature Fernández’s ‘Island Universe 2’ (2023), a large-scale, charcoal wall installation that elegantly combines all of the Earth’s landmasses, fusing them into one continuous, borderless terrain.

“The artists included in ‘Rewriting Histories’ explore complex histories often tied to colonialism, land, and power” states Respini. “Fernández’s monumental ‘Island Universe 2’ re-images global territories, visualizing the interconnected geological, cultural, and historical relationships of geographies. Made of charcoal, this installation illustrates so well Fernández’s interest in uncovering what she refers to as ‘stacked landscapes’—the conceptual framework that allows her work to reveal the often invisible, buried layers of historical violence embedded in land.”

Created specifically for this presentation, @Teresita.Fernandez’s ‘Island Universe 2’ disrupts conventions of mapmaking, representing the world’s continents and archipelagos as a single landmass evoking the early geologic supercontinent of Pangaea. Denaturalizing geographic and political borders, the artist’s provocative work fervently challenges traditional understandings of geography, landscape, and nation—in particular, the view of North as the inherently superior “up” and the reciprocal positioning of South as the inferior “down.”

Pictured: Island Universe 2, 2023 (detail). Charcoal, 77.6 x 303 x 3 inches (197.1 x 769.6 x 7.6 cm). Photo by Dan Bradica

Prepping a talk about past curatorial projects and enjoying re-visiting the @cindysherman retrospective I curated a decade ago at MoMA.  Her work presaged our current media age while also responding to it critically. Today, in the era of Tik Tok fame and reality tv shows, we take for granted that a photograph can be manipulated and identity is malleable.  Way before any of that, Cindy’s work underscored  photography’s complicity in the manufacturing of identity. Looking at these pictures never gets old - thanks Cindy for your brilliance and the gift of your work.

From photographing the Civil Rights Movement in the South in the 1960s to witnessing the aftermath of the displacement of Japanese Canadians forced into internment camps and the subsequent rebuilding of those communities alongside the Redress movement, photographer Tamio Wakayama left an indelible mark. Yet he is not widely known. Thanks to @therealpaulwong who introduced me to the work and spent time with me today sharing his photos and life story.

Tonight we open the gorgeous show “Rooted Here: Woven From the Land” featuring four prominent Coast Salish weavers:  qʷənat, Angela George (səlilwətaɬ/Tsleil-Waututh); Chepximiya Siyam’ Chief Janice George (Sḵwx̱wú7mesh/Squamish); Skwetsimeltxw Willard “Buddy” Joseph (Sḵwx̱wú7mesh/Squamish); and Qwasen, Debra Sparrow (xʷməθkʷəy̓əm/Musqueam) curated by my brilliant colleague Richard Hill. Come one, come all!

2023 was a year of big personal change and too much turmoil in the world.

I left a job and started another & moved to a new country and another coast.  My family and I made a home in the midst of all the new.

Rodney Graham’s tree pictures  are a reminder of our remarkable perceptual capacity - the eye receives an image upside down and the brain reverses it. Bringing this thought into 2024.

Happy new year all! 💫
